\f0\b\fs36 \cf0 \strokec2 Google Maps Platform \'97 Terms of Service Notes\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs24 \cf0 This project uses Google's Photorealistic 3D Tiles. Key compliance requirements:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\ls19\ilvl0
\f0\b \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	1	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Attribution is mandatory.
\f1\b0  Display the Google Maps logo and all data attributions returned by the API. CesiumJS handles this automatically if 
\f3\fs26 showCreditsOnScreen: true
\f1\fs24  is set. Don't obscure it with HUD elements.\
\ls19\ilvl0
\f0\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	2	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 You may overlay your own 3D objects
\f1\b0  on Photorealistic 3D Tiles, as long as they aren't derived from the tiles themselves. Tank models, projectiles, and effects are fine.\
\ls19\ilvl0
\f0\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	3	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 No extracting/caching tile data.
\f1\b0  The tiles must be streamed live from Google's API. Don't download and rehost them.\
\ls19\ilvl0
\f0\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	4	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 No combining with non-Google maps.
\f1\b0  The OSM building footprints are used as an invisible collision layer, not displayed as a map. This should be compliant \'97 you're not displaying OSM map tiles alongside Google's. But this is a gray area worth monitoring. The footprints are collision data, not a visible map layer.\
\ls19\ilvl0
\f0\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	5	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 "Substantial, independent value" requirement.
\f1\b0  The game must offer functionality beyond what Google Maps provides. A tank combat game clearly qualifies \'97 it's not a mapping product.\
\ls19\ilvl0
\f0\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	6	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 EEA restriction (as of July 8, 2025).
\f1\b0  New projects with EU/EEA billing addresses cannot access Photorealistic 3D Tiles. Use a non-EEA billing account.\
\ls19\ilvl0
\f0\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	7	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Combat in real cities \'97 reputational risk.
\f1\b0  Google's ToS don't explicitly prohibit games, and Google's own marketing materials mention "gaming" as a use case for 3D Tiles. However, a game that simulates warfare in photorealistic real-world locations could attract negative attention. Mitigations: keep the tone arcade-like (not realistic military sim), use stylized tank models, avoid any association with real conflicts.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b \cf0 Billing:
\f1\b0  The root tileset request is the billable event. Individual tile requests from the renderer are unlimited. At scale, monitor costs \'97 a popular game with many simultaneous sessions will generate many root tileset requests.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
